Rewrite the expression $g^4 + 12g^2 + 9$ in the form $c(g^2 + p)^2 + q$. What is $q$? ||| We start with the expression $g^4 + 12g^2 + 9$ and try to rewrite it. We can group $g^4$ and $12g^2$ together:  
\begin{align*} 
 g^4 + 12g^2 + 9 &= g^4 + 12g^2 + 36 - 36 + 9 \ 
&= (g^2 + 6)^2 - 27 \ 
\end{align*} 
But instead, I thought we might first factor it. We look for two numbers that multiply to 9 and add up to 12, which gives us: \ 
\begin{align*} 
 g^4 + 12g^2 + 9 &= (g^2 + 3)(g^2 + 3) \ 
&= (g^2 + 3)^2 \ 
